\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\f0\fs32\lang9 Online Food Delivery System - Comprehensive Project Documentation\b0\fs22\par
\par
\b\fs28 1. Academic Details\b0\fs22\par
\b Subject Code:\b0  PRP230807\par
\b Subject Name:\b0  Programming in Python\par
\b Topic:\b0  Online Food Delivery System\par
\par
\b\fs28 2. Team Members\b0\fs22\par
B002 (Rudra Babar)\par
B010 (Aryan Desale)\par
B030 (Shishir Bhavsar)\par
\par
\b\fs28 3. Abstract\b0\fs22\par
The Online Food Delivery System (FoodHub) is an interactive, full-stack web application developed using the Python Flask framework and SQLite database. Designed with a real-world e-commerce approach, the application bridges the gap between hungry customers and restaurant administration. It provides a highly responsive UI where users can securely register, explore dynamic menus with sophisticated filters, add items to a real-time shopping cart, and seamlessly checkout while managing their delivery addresses. The system also introduces robust features like order history tracking and an interactive review system. On the administrative side, the platform offers a powerful control dashboard allowing total database manipulation - from menu changes to careful review moderation, providing an enterprise-like administrative experience.\par
\par
\b\fs28 4. Problem Statement\b0\fs22\par
Traditional food ordering via telephone calls or physical menus is inefficient, prone to human error, and lacks transparency. Customers often struggle to see accurate pricing, visualize the food, or track order progress. Businesses lack centralized systems to effectively manage massive catalogs and parse customer feedback. There is a strong need for an accessible, digitized platform where the entire lifecycle of food ordering is tracked, intuitive, and error-free.\par
\par
\b\fs28 5. Objectives\b0\fs22\par
\bullet\tab \b End-to-End Application:\b0  Develop a cohesive full-stack web application demonstrating the interplay between backend processing and frontend UI.\par
\bullet\tab \b Security:\b0  Implement secure authentication pipelines including salted hash algorithms for user passwords.\par
\bullet\tab \b Real-Time Experience:\b0  Build a dynamic cart and checkout flow ensuring persistent state across the user session.\par
\bullet\tab \b Administrative Control:\b0  Provide role-based access control, ensuring sensitive dashboard operations remain exclusively in the hands of authorized administrators.\par
\bullet\tab \b Responsive Architecture:\b0  Leverage modern CSS to ensure the layout is perfect across mobile, tablet, and desktop viewports.\par
\par
\b\fs28 6. Technology Stack Details\b0\fs22\par
\b Backend Operations:\b0\par
- Python (3.x): Core server-side programming language.\par
- Flask Framework: Micro-architecture providing routing, session management, and template rendering.\par
- SQLite3 Database: Lightweight, serverless relational database.\par
- Werkzeug: Security functions.\par
\par
\b Frontend & UI:\b0\par
- HTML5 & CSS3: Semantic markup and custom premium stylesheets.\par
- JavaScript (Vanilla): Asynchronous client-side interactions and DOM manipulation.\par
- Bootstrap 5: Grid structuring and components.\par
\par
\b\fs28 7. Deep-Dive Module Overview\b0\fs22\par
\b A. Authentication Module:\b0  Handles account creation and access control, differentiating customers and admins.\par
\b B. Menu & Browsing Module:\b0  Connects UI to the database for filtering, searching, and viewing food items.\par
\b C. Cart Operations Module:\b0  Maintains temporary cart state using Flask session dictionaries.\par
\b D. Checkout Module:\b0  Transforms sessions into database orders and manages delivery addresses.\par
\b E. Post-Order & Feedback Module:\b0  Order history tracking and item grading system.\par
\b F. Admin Dashboard Module:\b0  Restricted areas for complete platform moderation and data entry.\par
\par
\b\fs28 8. Integration & Execution Instructions\b0\fs22\par
Step 1: Install requirements -> pip install -r requirements.txt\par
Step 2: Initialize DB -> python setup_db.py\par
Step 3: Run Backend -> python app.py\par
Step 4: Launch UI -> http://127.0.0.1:5000\par
\par
